<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1437,152,971]" pageId="27" pageNumber="178">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,800,827]" pageId="27" pageNumber="178">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Monteiro &amp; Barbosa &amp; Esposito, 2019" authorityName="Monteiro &amp; Barbosa &amp; Esposito" authorityYear="2019" box="[343,608,801,827]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Phytomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="178" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varronivora" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[343,608,801,827]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="178">Phytomyza varronivora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[617,707,801,827]" pageId="27" pageNumber="178" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[617,707,801,827]" pageId="27" pageNumber="178">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Zetterstedt" authorityName="Zetterstedt" authorityYear="1860" box="[858,1229,801,827]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Phytomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="178" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crassiseta">
<emphasis box="[858,1100,801,827]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="178">Phytomyza crassiseta</emphasis>
Zetterstedt
</taxonomicName>
due to the basally enlarged arista, but it is differentiated by the well-developed epandrium, occupying approximately half the length of the abdomen. The inner arms of the epandrium and the distiphallus are characteristics of this species and essentials for differentiating it from other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fallen" authorityYear="1810" box="[504,627,909,935]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Phytomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="178" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[504,627,909,935]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="178">Phytomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species. Larvae forme serpentine mines on the leaf surface and pupation takes place on the ground. This is the first Agromyzdae species known to feed on 
<taxonomicName authority="P. Browne." authorityName="P. Browne." box="[1067,1295,945,971]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Varronia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Boraginales" pageId="27" pageNumber="178" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1067,1166,946,971]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="178">Varronia</emphasis>
P. Browne.
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
